From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Manish KL <manish@example.com>
Date: Sat, 2 May 2026 00:00:00 +0530
Subject: [RFC PATCH 0/7] sched/cpufreq: agent-aware DVFS windows

Agentic AI workloads execute short control loops separated by waits on
network, disk, timer, or io_uring completions. On power-managed ARM
systems, those waits can be long enough for schedutil/cpuidle to reduce
performance state, but short enough that the next completion immediately
pays frequency-ramp and idle-exit latency.

This RFC introduces an experimental CONFIG_AGENT_LATENCY feature that
adds a bounded "agent active window" to the scheduler runqueue. While a
window is active, schedutil observes a minimum effective utilization and
cpuidle can avoid idle states whose exit latency exceeds a configurable
agent latency budget.

This is a research patch skeleton, not upstream-ready. It is intended for
local kernel branch experimentation, Codex/Gemini refinement, and blog/paper
artifact development.

Patch layout:
  [1/7] sched: add SCHED_FLAG_AGENT_LATENCY and task helpers
  [2/7] sched: track agent active window on rq
  [3/7] sched/fair: refresh agent window on wakeup
  [4/7] sched/cpufreq: apply agent min-util boost in schedutil
  [5/7] cpuidle: add agent latency guard helper
  [6/7] trace: add agent latency DVFS tracepoints
  [7/7] tools: add minimal agent_loop microbenchmark

Design notes:
  - Builds on schedutil rather than replacing CPUFreq.
  - Complements uclamp; uclamp is a performance hint while this models a
    short active control-loop window.
  - Does not create a real-time class and does not bypass fairness.
  - A production version must include cgroup budgets, thermal constraints,
    and admin policy to prevent hint abuse.

References:
  - Documentation/admin-guide/pm/cpufreq.rst
  - Documentation/scheduler/sched-util-clamp.rst
  - Documentation/trace/events-power.rst
  - kernel/sched/cpufreq_schedutil.c
  - drivers/cpuidle/

